                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/2463</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Military Attaché in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McIlroy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Adjutant General of the Army</hi>
                        (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bridges</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="4" xml:id="d273fn4">Copy of radiogram transmitted to the
                        Department of State by the War Department, October 21.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-10-21">October 21,
                            1931</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>No. 190. Full General Tanaka,<note n="*" xml:id="d273fn5">Unable to identify
                        definitely. Believed to be General Kunishige Tanaka who was Military Attaché
                        in Washington &amp; London, aide-de-camp to the Emperor, headed military
                        delegates to Washington Conference. WCC. (Major Crane) [Footnote in the
                        original by Maj. W. C. Crane.]</note> Retired, calling at my house last
                    night by appointment stated very emphatically “I ask you to cable your Secretary
                    of War that the fighting men of Japan will not permit the League of Nations or
                    America to intervene in any way that might weaken Japan’s position in
                    Manchuria.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MoIlroy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
